{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618719"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:24:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:24:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16513"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16513"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65544"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7158"},{"type":"tags","id":"10331"},{"type":"tags","id":"10342"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21828"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21833"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65544","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65544"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for assessment of chronic neuropathic pain. During the consultation, you explain the different pathways involved in pain perception. She asks about the specific roles of different tracts in the anterolateral system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes the roles of these tracts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Spinoreticular tract: conscious detection of pain/temperature; Spinomesencephalic tract: emotional and arousal response to pain; Spinothalamic tract: modulation of pain","Spinoreticular tract: modulation of pain; Spinomesencephalic tract: emotional and arousal response to pain; Spinothalamic tract: conscious detection of pain/temperature","Spinoreticular tract: emotional and arousal response to pain; Spinomesencephalic tract: modulation of pain; Spinothalamic tract: conscious detection of pain/temperature","Spinoreticular tract: modulation of pain; Spinomesencephalic tract: conscious detection of pain/temperature; Spinothalamic tract: emotional and arousal response to pain","Spinoreticular tract: emotional and arousal response to pain; Spinomesencephalic tract: conscious detection of pain/temperature; Spinothalamic tract: modulation of pain"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the roles of different pain pathways is crucial for comprehending pain perception and its management. The anterolateral system consists of three main tracts, each with distinct functions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espinothalamic tract\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary pathway for conscious perception of pain and temperature sensations. It projects directly to the thalamus, which then relays information to the somatosensory cortex for conscious interpretation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espinoreticular tract\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for mediating emotional and arousal responses to pain. It projects to the reticular formation in the brainstem, which is involved in arousal and autonomic responses to painful stimuli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espinomesencephalic tract\u003C/strong\u003E plays a role in pain modulation. It projects to the periaqueductal grey matter in the midbrain, which is involved in descending pain modulation systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other combinations presented in the options incorrectly assign these roles to different tracts. Understanding these pathways is important as they represent different aspects of pain processing - conscious perception, emotional response, and modulation - which can be targeted separately in pain management strategies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The spinothalamic tract is responsible for conscious detection of pain and temperature sensations.","The spinoreticular tract mediates emotional and arousal responses to pain.","The spinomesencephalic tract is involved in modulation of pain signals."],"references":["Kang JH, Im S. Functional Anatomy of the Spinal Tracts Based on Evolutionary Perspectives. Korean J Neurotrauma. 2023 Sep 12;19(3):275-287. doi: 10.13004/kjnt.2023.19.e43. PMID: 37840623; PMCID: PMC10567534.","Willis WD, Westlund KN. Neuroanatomy of the pain system and of the pathways that modulate pain. J Clin Neurophysiol. 1997 Jan;14(1):2-31. doi: 10.1097/00004691-199701000-00002. PMID: 9013357; PMCID: PMC7859971.","Dum RP, Levinthal DJ, Strick PL. The spinothalamic system targets motor and sensory areas in the cerebral cortex of monkeys. J Neurosci. 2009 Nov 11;29(45):14223-35. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.3398-09.2009. PMID: 19906970; PMCID: PMC2796243.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16513"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:26:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:54:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"ty